h3. Issue Summary

Setting an issue source where the overall sum of issues in the board exceeds 5000 fails even if selecting a version that has less than the limit
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create sample 6000 issues;
 # Create 10 versions;
 # Assign 500 issues to one of the versions;
 # Do not assign other issues to other versions;
 # Navigate to a Portfolio Plan and change the issue source;
 # Select a board or a project containing all 6000 issues;
 # Select the version containing only 500 issues;

h3. Expected Results

The plan is created with the 500 issues on the release;
h3. Actual Results

Source selection fails with:
{quote}Your current selection includes too many issues to load correctly. Refine your selection to connect to fewer releases or projects.
{quote}
Inspecting the API retrieval of issues, it returns 5000 even if only less than 500 are selected (in this particular test) and no versions are selected despite the UI element being highlighted.
 !image-2020-01-03-14-27-58-323.png|thumbnail! 
 !image-2020-01-03-14-28-29-097.png|thumbnail!
h3. Workaround
 * Create a new board that filters for the specific {{fixVersion}} value and use that board as a source for the plan.

 * Use a filter as the issue source that collects issues from that {{fixVersion}}

 * Include all issues in a dummy release so they are not picked up. It seems like the selection picks up what is in that release and what has no releases associated.

h3. Problem Definition

The current WARN logging when a user is trying to edit a Team field is not clear.
{code}
2019-09-18 18:05:17,688 http-nio-8080-exec-24 WARN username 111x111x1 xxxxxx x.x.x.x /secure/QuickEditIssue.jspa [c.a.r.t.customfields.team.TeamCustomFieldTypeHelper] Editability check for setting Portfolio team field failed
{code}

The *Editability check for setting Portfolio team field failed* message reported only when the user tries to edit a subtask (because we don't allow editing team for a subtask) or when there is an invalid license.

h3. Suggested Solution

Mention the reason for the failure in the logging for clarity. Example:
{quote}
Editability check for setting Portfolio team field failed due to editing a subtask/licence invalid
{quote}
 
h3. Workaround 
(Optional)

h3. Problem Definition
It would be useful to see the "Epic Status" field of an epic present in the "Child issues" panel of an Initiative to clearly identify Epics that have been "marked as done" from the Board's epic panel as described [here|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftwareserver/working-with-epics-938845394.html] & [here|https://www.atlassian.com/agile/tutorials/epics]  for a clear identifier of which child epics are complete and will not be displayed on the board, without having to dig into each child epic independently, as the Status and Epic status can have alternate values

h3. Suggested Solution
Add Epic Status field in the Initiative Child Issues panel 
 
h3. Workaround
You can use the following Script injection via the announcement banner (Tested and verified against Jira 8.0 and 8.4 without error in test data) But this comes with a word of caution as script injection in this manner can trigger unforeseen errors in other locations in the system, so if you have any page loading errors after enabling this remove the script as part of the troubleshooting process.
* Locate the Custom field ID for the epic status
** navigate to *Admin >> Issues >> Field Configurations >> Default Field Configuration* locate the Epic Status field and select the Screens option for the field and the CustomField_ID value will be located in the URL for the screen setting page.
* sourced and Modified from [this script exe|https://community.developer.atlassian.com/t/how-to-add-status-column-to-child-issues-panel-in-an-initiative-jira-portfolio-for-jira/1967], Add the following script to the announcement banner, Noting that *customfield_XXXX* will be your epic status field ID:
{code}
<script type='text/javascript'>
AJS.$(document).ready(function() {
AJS.$('#jpo-child-issues-web-panel .jpo-child-issue-table tr').each(function() {
  var $row = AJS.$(this);
  var issueKey = $row.find('td:first-child').text();
  AJS.$.getJSON(AJS.contextPath() + '/rest/api/latest/issue/' + issueKey, function(data){
        var epicStatus = data.fields.customfield_XXXX.value;
        if (epicStatus  == 'To Do') {
            $row.append('<td class="jira-issue-status-lozenge aui-lozenge jira-issue-status-lozenge-blue jira-issue-status-lozenge-done aui-lozenge-subtle jira-issue-status-lozenge-max-width-medium">' + epicStatus + '</td>');
          }
          else if (epicStatus == 'In Progress') {
            $row.append('<td class="jira-issue-status-lozenge aui-lozenge jira-issue-status-lozenge-yellow jira-issue-status-lozenge-done aui-lozenge-subtle jira-issue-status-lozenge-max-width-medium">' + epicStatus + '</td>');
          }
          else {
            $row.append('<td class="jira-issue-status-lozenge aui-lozenge jira-issue-status-lozenge-green jira-issue-status-lozenge-done aui-lozenge-subtle jira-issue-status-lozenge-max-width-medium">' + epicStatus + '</td>');
          }
        });
  });
});
</script>
{code}

h3. Issue Summary

When upgrading past version 2.20, Portfolio for Jira adds a new {{Issue Link Type}} "Parent-Child Link" as part of the upgrade tasks for that version.

If this link is already present in the database for whatever reason, a new link will be created anyway, resulting in a duplicate {{Issue Link Type}} in the database.

While Portfolio for Jira does not create the link twice, it is possible that the link has already been created by an external influence, for example, the popular Issue migration plugin, Configuration Manager for Jira
h3. Environment
 * Portfolio for Jira version <= 2.20 that has later been upgraded to or past version 2.20

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Setup two Jira instances, one on JPOS version < 2.20 (instance A), the other >= 2.20 (instance B)
 # On (instance A), create a test project with Sample data.
 # On (instance A), create a portfolio and link it to the test project
 # On (instance A), create two tasks under an epic, and ensure the epic is listed as Parent under the "Parent" column (you might need to click the [...] button to show the parent column)
 # Migrate a project from (instance B) to (instance A) using a third party App that moves the "Parent-Child Link" {{Issue Link Type}} (for example, Configuration Manager for Jira)
 # Upgrade (instance A) Portfolio for Jira to a version >= 2.20
 # Observe that a duplicate "Parent-Child Link" {{Issue Link Type}} has been created
{code:sql}
SELECT * from issuelinktype WHERE linkname = 'Parent-Child Link'{code}

h3. Expected Results

Execute the query
{code:sql}
SELECT * FROM issuelinktype WHERE linkname = 'Parent-Child Link'{code}
Only 1 "Parent-Child Link" {{Issue Link Type}} is present in the database
h3. Actual Results

Execute the query
{code:sql}
SELECT * FROM issuelinktype WHERE linkname = 'Parent-Child Link'{code}
Two "Parent-Child Link" {{Issue Link Type}} are present in the database
h3. Workaround

If you have duplicate a duplicate Parent-Child issueLinkType in your database, it is safe to delete the extra one provided that it has no Issues associated to it via {{issuelink}}.
 # Check the number of issuelinktypes with the following query
{code:sql}
SELECT * FROM issuelinktype WHERE linkname = 'Parent-Child Link'{code}
Note down the {{id}} values returned for use in the next step. 

 # If two results are returned, check if one of the {{IssueLinkType}} has no issue links associated with the following query
{code:sql}
SELECT t.id, t.linkname, l.linktype, l.source, l.destination FROM issuelink l, issuelinktype t WHERE t.linkname = 'Parent-Child Link' AND t.id = l.linktype order by t.id;
{code}
If there are no rows returned, or, if all rows returned have the same {{id}}, the {{IssueLinkType}} with the {{id}} +not+ present in the set can be deleted.

 # Shutdown all Jira nodes and perform a backup of the database
 # Execute the following query
{code:sql}
DELETE FROM issuelinktype WHERE id = <ID OF THE issuelinktype with no issue links associated>{code}
